#DESCRIPTION
#  Find local maximum and minimum of f(x)=ax+6x^(-1)
#ENDDESCRIPTION
## Author('Utah ww group')
## Institution('Univeristy of Utah')
## DBsubject('Calculus')
## DBchapter('Applications of Differentiation')
## DBsection('Maximum and Minimum Values')
## AuthorText1('Dale Varberg, Edwin J. Purcell, and Steven E. Rigdon')
## TitleText1('Calculus')
## EditionText1('9')
## Section1('Applications of the Derivative')
## Problem1('')
## KEYWORDS('calculus')

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a1 = random(2,9,1);
$b1 = random(2,9,1);
$c1 = sqrt($b1/$a1);
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
The function \( f(x) = $a1 x + $b1 x ^ { -1 } \)
has one local minimum and one local maximum. $BR
It is helpful to make a rough sketch of the graph to see what is happening. $BR
This function has a local minimum at \( x \) equals \{ans_rule(20) \}
EOT
$ans = $c1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
with value \{ans_rule(20) \} $BR
EOT
$ans = $a1*$c1 + $b1/$c1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
and a local maximum at \( x \) equals \{ans_rule(20) \}
EOT
$ans = -$c1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
with value \{ans_rule(20) \}
EOT
$ans = -$a1*$c1 - $b1/$c1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
